I'm not that experienced at giving criticism because I'm not a great writer or an experienced critic when it comes to written works. Take what I say with a grain of salt.

It's good, but very flawed.

I'll start with stuff that I enjoyed. I like Akina. I thought the description was cute and she has a charming amount of optimism that didn't feel forced. I thought it made an interesting contrast to the harsh war-torn nation she grew up in. I liked that. I also liked that you handled the conflict with a level of nuance. It's not always about starting a fight for race or tribal allegiance. It could be as simple as a scarcity of resources or land, although some groups certainly use it as an excuse for ethnic cleansing or atrocity. I thought that your portrayal captured that well.

What I didn't like: The ending was rushed, and it shows. Conflicting actions within the same lines and distracting grammatical errors make it feel like the writer didn't take the time to give those parts of the story even a once over, and it REALLY takes you out of the story. I also think that it did a huge disservice that you didn't have Akina wake before the epilogue. This is a woman who's having her whole life upended, who had her house and life destoyed and has to leave the country and her parents behind. It's such a wasted opportunity for the character growth of Akina, and probably Anon as well. I don't want to call anyone out here but it really felt like the author didn't know where he wanted the story to go and it's such a shame because there were plenty of directions it could have gone.

Anonymous Sat 25 Apr 2020 21:53:55 No.29851058 Report
Quoted By: >>29852383
>>29849586
Mention it once or twice and have the main character note that certain words sound funny in their voice, or that they struggle with certain syllables.
I'd avoid writing it how it sounds exactly, on the principle that it can make things harder to understand for the reader and could potentially get annoying after a while.
Let's say you have a bee character, and they buzz and shit when they speak. Their dialogue is going to read like "Hello faggotzzz, zzwhich one of you bitchezz wantz zzome honey?" hopefully you'd write it with a little more subtlety than that, but hey it's just an example.
Now, it's got the potential to be funny or interesting the first time around because it's weird and off-beat, but consider how long your story is, and how much of this weird and off-beat dialogue your reader is going to have to wade through. After a while they're going to get pissed off and wish your bee guy just talked like a regular person.
Then there's the matter of doing it for your other characters. If you just do it for the bee guy, people are going to think it's weird that he's the only bug with a speech impediment. What if there's multiple insects in your story? Now you're going to have to write weird dialogue for all of them, and the reader is going to have to put up with it.
